        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1006144359" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12799219877932895234">This is one book, of which I told to myself as I turned the last page; I should have read it much much earlier. At the end the stories give you the taste and smell of a novel. The stories tell you that one need not go about searching for a niche material to tell a story. The small things of life in the very surrounding around you have a lot of content for a good story. You have to capture the essence - the essential humor element,sufferings,joys man experiences in the mid of community life. Spea</span>
  <span id="freeText12799219877932895234" style="display:none">This is one book, of which I told to myself as I turned the last page; I should have read it much much earlier. At the end the stories give you the taste and smell of a novel. The stories tell you that one need not go about searching for a niche material to tell a story. The small things of life in the very surrounding around you have a lot of content for a good story. You have to capture the essence - the essential humor element,sufferings,joys man experiences in the mid of community life. Speaking the unspeakable without being vulgar while generating humor at the same time is an art Mistry has mastered. How easily, like a magician he convert's Sarosh's individual bowel problem into a huge 'immigration-related' metaphor. And how smoothly does he give a character his individuality - 'And now, Nariman allowed his low-pitched rumbles to turn into chuckles.' And how abstractions get concrete shapes! .And...so forth. <br />A GREAT read </span>
  <a data-text-id="12799219877932895234" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
